INTRODUCTION

We are trying to understand the relationship between GDP per capita and the number of working hours worked per week.

The motivation for us to choose this topic was because it is the general idea that if people work longer, they are obligated to earn more. There is a common cultural sentiment to work longer to expect more monetary rewards. Logically and morally it does seem appropriate that the more the effort put in by an individual, the more they would be compensated.

This idea has always appeased Hardworking individuals however we want to understand if there is substantial evidence backing this idea or is this a thought of the past which may not bear much fruits in todays day and age.

To keep things uniform, all comparisons done are over multiple countries across the world, this helps eliminate bias against any single country. This does not consider ethnicity or other parameters which may introduce biases, it simply looks at Income as GDP per capital and the actual number of hours worked per week.

To achieve this, we have undertaken the following tasks :

  • Data Import and loading from Downloaded files.

  • Data Transformation and cleaning

  • Data Visualization, Regression and Correlation

  • Cluster Analysis

  • Results and Observations

This topic is novel to us because it goes beyond the rationale thought process to work harder to maximize wealth, if proved true, the evidence provided must support this view from the data provided.

1. DATA IMPORTING AND LOADING

We read in our CSV Data. The data files used are from the gapminder website which are readily available for download.

workingHoursData = read.csv("working_hours_per_week.csv");
gdpData = read.csv("gdp_pcap.csv")
countries_by_income = read.csv("country_income.csv")

The original dataset of Working_hours_per_week and gdp_pcap does not have region wise segregation and income wise segregation information. In order to get this information, We append the data columns with countries_by_income created using data from gapminder against the GDP per capita and working hours per week. This provides additional categories of Region and IncomeGroup to our data which helps us summarize and analyze our data effectively.

gdpData <- countries_by_income %>% left_join(gdpData, by = c("Name" = "country"))
workingHoursData <- countries_by_income %>% left_join(workingHoursData, by = c("Name" = "country"))

2. DATA CLEANING AND TRANSFORMATION

In the GDP Data Frame, we can see that some column fields have a numeric description such as 5320 etc, but some has a character description such as 31.4k or 32.1k. Therefore we will first need to clean our data, handle NA values, convert the character into numeric format and represent the number in decimal format, for example, we need to represent 31.4k as 31400

We also have another issue that the years is not represented as a column, rather a row. We will not be able to combine data if the year is depicted as rows and hence we will have to use pivot_longer to transform the years as rows into columns.

We can first write a function to perform the above, to check the character in each cell and convert them into numeric field. We can then apply the function on each column to transform the data.

convert_values <- function(x) {
  if(is.na(x) || x == "") {
    return(NA)
  } else if(grepl("^[0-9.]+k$", x)) {
    return(as.numeric(substr(x, 1, nchar(x) - 1)) * 1000)
  } else if(grepl("^[0-9.]+$", x)) {
    return(as.numeric(x))
  } else {
    return(x)
  }
}

gdpData <- as.data.frame(lapply(gdpData, function(col) {
  if (is.character(col)) {
    return(sapply(col, convert_values))
  } else {
    return(col)
  }
}))

workingHoursData <- as.data.frame(lapply(workingHoursData, function(col) {
  if (is.character(col) || is.double(col)) {
    return(sapply(col, convert_values))
  } else {
    return(col)
  }
}))

working_hours_week_long <- workingHoursData %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = starts_with("X"), 
               names_to = "year", 
               values_to = "working_hours")

gdp_data_long <- gdpData %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = starts_with("X"), 
               names_to = "year", 
               values_to = "gdp")

3. DATA VISUALIZATION, REGRESSION AND CORRELATION

In order to understand the relationship between the working hours per week and gdp per data, we can use scatter plots to understand relations between them. Since we have many countries and we want to find a relation between GDP and working hours per week, it would be better to start by grouping countries based on Income levels to check for any patterns or relations compared to Region which may not give the best indications when we are looking for trends in Income/GDP.

precheck_df_workWeek <- working_hours_week_long %>% 
  group_by(year, IncomeGroup) %>% 
  summarize(WorkWeek_mean = mean(working_hours, na.rm = TRUE))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
precheck_df_gdp <- gdp_data_long %>% 
  group_by(year, IncomeGroup) %>% 
  summarize(gdp_mean = mean(gdp, na.rm = TRUE))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

On Looking at the above Scatter Plot of Average GDP of countries by IncomeGroup we can see a clear trend on High income countries of growing GDP over the number of years. It is intriguing however to see a very moderate rise in GDP in Upper middle income countries and Lower middle income countries.

Moving to Working Hours per week, the below code will generate a scatter plot to examine relations in working hours per week between countries based on Incomegroup.

ggplot(data = precheck_df_workWeek, aes(x = year, y = WorkWeek_mean, color = IncomeGroup)) +
    geom_point() +
 labs(title = "Average Work Week of countries by IncomeGroup")

Here we see that the upper middle income group has a decreasing number of working hours per week, although there are some missing points at certain intervals and is generally decreasing, it is not decreasing at a rapid rate, we see a similar situation with the Lower middle income class group, in this case, the decrease of working hours per week is minimal. However in case of the High income groups, the drop is the least compared to all others, it tends to stay constant in a small interval. The discrepency of decrease of number of working hours per week between different groups pushes us to investigate further.

Since we are finding relationships between GDP and number of working hours per week for a set of countries based on income as a whole, and not solely each individual country, it wouldnt be meaningful to consider working hours and GDP for individual countries, rather we would need to consider group of countries and hence we will have to use average GDP and average working hours per week of the constituent countries associated with an Income Group.

3.1 CORRELATION OF GDP AND NUMBER OF WORKING HOURS IN UPPER MIDDLE INCOME COUNTRIES

upperMiddleIncomeCountry_gdp_data <- gdp_data_long %>% filter(IncomeGroup == "Upper middle income")
upperMiddleIncomeCountry_work_week_data <- working_hours_week_long %>% filter(IncomeGroup == "Upper middle income")

upperMiddleIncomeCountry_gdp_data_mean <- upperMiddleIncomeCountry_gdp_data %>% 
  group_by(year, IncomeGroup) %>% 
  summarize(avg_gdp = mean(gdp, na.rm = TRUE))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
upperMiddleIncomeCountry_work_week_data_mean <- upperMiddleIncomeCountry_work_week_data %>% 
  group_by(year, IncomeGroup) %>% 
  summarize(avg_working_hours = mean(working_hours, na.rm = TRUE))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
# Since we want to compare gdp data with working hours per week, they both are on different timeframes, we will use the log function to scale them both to the same measurement.
#NOTE: This is not a true value of gdp or working hours per week but rather a scaled representation.
# We divide by 52 because our gdp per capita data is based on yearly data while we are comparing it to number of hours worked per week and hence we are converting both into a weekly timeframe.

upperMiddleIncomeCountry_gdp_data_mean$avg_gdp <- log((upperMiddleIncomeCountry_gdp_data_mean$avg_gdp)/52)
upperMiddleIncomeCountry_work_week_data_mean$avg_working_hours <- log(upperMiddleIncomeCountry_work_week_data_mean$avg_working_hours)
upperMiddleIncomeCountry_work_week_data_mean

We can see an increase in GDP per capita of these groups of countries, it corresponds to a shift in number of working hours. On careful inspection of the graph, we can see that number of working hours decreases over time, as GDP per capita increases.

Now that we have a basic understanding of this relationship, we can form a regression to understand the relationship between these values.

model_upperMiddle_income <- lm(avg_working_hours ~ avg_gdp, data = combined_data_upperMiddleIncomeCountry)
summary(model_upperMiddle_income)

For the Countries falling under the Upper Middle Income category, we can see a negative correlation, for every increase in gdp per capita, the corresponding average working hour per week in the group of countries decreases by a factor of -3.9

We can perform a similar analysis for High Income countries and Low Income countries as well.

It is seen that an increase in GDP per capita of High income group of countries is inversely proportional to number of working hours per week. On careful inspection of the graph, we can see that number of working hours decreases over time as GDP per capita increases but by a smaller margin compared to previous working hours trendline.

Just like before, we can form a regression to understand the relationship between these values.

model_High_income <- lm(avg_working_hours ~ avg_gdp + 0, data = combined_data_HighIncomeCountry)
summary(model_High_income)

This data shows some interesting information, in this case as well, the slope of the regression equation is negative, implying that as there is a single unit of change in the increase in GDP in High income countries, there is a corresponding decrease of a factor of -6.6 for the average working hours. Its interesting to note that we saw a similar behaviour in upper middle income countries, however this changes by a larger factor than what is seen previously.

This seems to be interesting, although the initial graph did not give a direction for the number of working hours per week, the regression equation indicates a very slight change with the dependent variable. a small factor of 0.0085, which means a unit change in the gdp per capita of an individual in a country from the low income group has seen a reduction in working hours over the year by a factor of 0.0085. This is not a large change compared to what is seen previously.

We come to an important finding while checking the three groups. The relation between the Average gdp per capita of an individual in each country compared to number of working hours per week is as follows:

    1. For High Income Countries              : y = 31 - 6.6x
    2. For Upper Middle Income Countries      : y = 20 - 3.9x
    3. For Low Income Countries               : y = 3.6 - 0.0085x

We can see that the magnitude of shift in working hours per week decreases as we move from Higher income countries to lower income countries. This can be shown in a cluster analysis as well.

4. CLUSTER ANALYSIS

4.1 USING ELBOW METHOD TO FIND APPROPRIATE K-VALUES.

kfind_df_cluster <- rbind(combined_data_HighIncomeCountry, combined_data_upperMiddleIncomeCountry, combined_data_LowIncomeCountry)
kfind_clustering_data <- kfind_df_cluster[, c("avg_working_hours", "avg_gdp")]

wss <- (nrow(kfind_clustering_data)-1)*sum(apply(kfind_clustering_data,2,var))
for (i in 2:10) {
  set.seed(123)
  wss[i] <- sum(kmeans(kfind_clustering_data, centers=i)$withinss)
}

elbow_df <- data.frame(k = 2:10, WSS = wss[2:10])

ggplot(elbow_df, aes(x = k, y = WSS)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 2:10) +
  labs(x = "Number of clusters k", y = "Total within-clusters sum of squares (WSS)") +
  theme_minimal()

4.2 PLOTTING THE CLUSTERS

combined_df_cluster <- rbind(combined_data_HighIncomeCountry, combined_data_upperMiddleIncomeCountry, combined_data_LowIncomeCountry)
clustering_data <- combined_df_cluster[, c("avg_working_hours", "avg_gdp")]

set.seed(123)

km_result <- kmeans(clustering_data, centers = 3)
combined_df_cluster$cluster <- km_result$cluster

As we can see, the cluster explains the situation, we have 3 distinct clusters based on High Income, Low Income and Upper Middle Income. Each of them have a comparable difference in GDP per capita, hence we see High income countries as a cluster over 6, Upper middle income countries between 5.5 and 5.8 while lower income countries having a low average GDP under 4. It is also evident from the level of dispersion seen for the Average working hours of each cluster that justifies the low coefficient values as we move from Higher income countries to lower income countries. as seen here. The High income countries range from 3.6 to roughly 3.67 which is a small range compared to Upper middle income countries which range from 3.65 to roughly 3.85. We then further see a wider range in lower income countries where they range from roughly 3.3 till 3.9 which is the largest range. All the categories however had an increase in GDP per capita over the number of year.

4.3 CONCLUSION

There is no evidence to state that there is a positive correlation between average gdp per capita in any of the countries compared to number of hours worked per week, i.e the more work produced each hour does not translate into an increase in gdp per capita. On the other hand, a decline is observed, and the decline is steeper as we move from Richer countries to Poorer countries.

The Data is spread from 1977 till 2020 which is a large period and across this time frame, it is observed that the number of working hours per week have reduced while gdp per capita has increased. this ratio is more for richer countries and lesser for poorer countries. This may be due to the access of superior technology and infrastructure in richer countries resulting into employees being more productive and getting more work done in the same time as compared to poorer countries. Therefore to conclude, there is actually a negative correlation between average gdp per capita and number of hours worked per week from 1977 till 2020.

We were also able to also conclude that gdp earned by a employee/worker depends on country and the same amount of work may not produce the same amount of gdp across the world.
